article.headline: Suns end five-game home skid
article.linkText: Suns play like teams of yore, beat Milwaukee
article.story:
PHOENIX (AP) -- On a night when perennial All-Star Charles Barkley was honored by the Suns, the current edition of the team played like the Phoenix teams of the past. Amare Stoudemire scored 27 points and the Suns reached a season high in points and broke a five-game home losing streak by beating the Milwaukee Bucks 123-111 on Saturday night. "Maybe Barkley brought us some luck today," Joe Johnson said. A capacity crowd of 18,422 came to see Barkley inducted into the Ring of Honor, and they were rewarded with the team's best performance of the season. "When the house is full, we excel," Shawn Marion said. The victory was the Suns' 16th in a row at home over the slumping Bucks. Overall, the Suns have won only seven of their last 27 games, while Milwaukee has lost seven of eight. Stoudemire, who has scored 20 or more points in 16 of the last 18 games, also grabbed eight rebounds, helping the Suns to a 40-35 advantage on the boards. The second-year pro was moved by the halftime ceremonies honoring Barkley. "It was great to see," Stoudemire said, "especially for a guy like Barkley who played so hard throughout his career. He's a role model for a lot of guys. "The fans were lovely. I saw the support they had for Charles." Johnson added 21 points for the Suns, Marion had 19 points and nine rebounds, rookie Maciej Lampe scored a season-high 17 and Casey Jacobsen had 12. Joe Smith tied a season high in leading the Bucks with 19 points. Keith Van Horn scored 13 and ex-Sun Brevin Knight had 12. In a fast-paced first half, the suddenly run-and-gun Suns had their highest output of the season, racing to a 68-56 lead. Among the biggest contributors were the reserves -- Lampe, Howard Eisley and Jacobsen. The three accounted for 22 points, On Friday night, the Suns' substitutes scored only six points during a 93-80 loss to Minnesota. Stoudemire, despite being limited to 15 minutes because of foul trouble, led the way with 15 points, and Marion scored 12 as the Suns shot 58.1 percent (25-for 43). Included in that output was a pinpoint 8-for-11 from 3-point range. The Suns finished 10-for-18 from beyond the arc, while the Bucks wound up 0-for-6 -- the first time this season an opponent has failed to hit a 3-pointer against the Suns. The Bucks were even hotter in the first half, hitting 58.5 percent (24-for-41), but they couldn't connect from long distance. "They shot the ball extremely well from 3," Milwaukee coach Terry Porter said. "They did good things. But when we allowed them to get into the open court, they did pretty much whatever they wanted." Smith also thought the difference was the Suns' 3-point shooting. "If you're knocking down the 3 like that, whether we're shooting 50 percent or not, it's going to be a long night for us," he said. Stoudemire picked up his fourth personal with only 2:40 gone in the third period and went to the bench, but the Suns' offense didn't falter, keeping up the pressure against the defensively challenged Bucks. After three quarters, Phoenix led 96-79. The Bucks only made the score respectable by scoring the game's final 10 points.

Game notes
Suns center Jake Voskuhl missed his third straight game with an injured left arch. ... The Bucks' last victory in Phoenix was Feb. 21, 1987. ... The Suns' 15-21 record at home assures they will have their first losing home record since their inaugural year of 1968-69. ... Johnson played at least 40 minutes for the 23rd consecutive game. ... Phoenix's previous season high was 121 against Dallas on Nov. 26.
